page.title: 03Wildlife in Swineshead
page.content: Every Spring many frogs become road casualties in their yearly migration to the ponds around Moat Farm and Sandy Lane area. As time passes the ponds become full of tadpoles. As you approach Swineshead from any direction you become aware of the amount of trees in and around the village. These are mainly deciduous and consist of elm, ash and oak. Although in recent years Dutch Elm disease has taken a toll of the elm population. However, tree planting will help make up the losses. Swineshead is quite fortunate in the amount and variety of bird life due to its position and varied types of cover. The birds quite commonly seen around Swineshead include; woodpeckers, blackcaps, whitethroats, numerous warblers, flycatchers, owls, gamebirds plus the commoner species.
